questions.specification:
An online education platform tracks students and their courses. The platform has a `Student` class and a `Course` class.

```java
public class Course {
    private String courseName;
    private int courseCode;
    private Student[] enrolledStudents;

    public Course(String courseName, int courseCode, int capacity) {
        this.courseName = courseName;
        this.courseCode = courseCode;
        this.enrolledStudents = new Student[capacity];
    }

    public void enrollStudent(Student student) {
        // code to add a student to the enrolledStudents array
    }
}

public class Student {
    private String studentID;
    private String name;
    private boolean activeStatus;

    public Student(String studentID, String name) {
        this.studentID = studentID;
        this.name = name;
        this.activeStatus = true;
    }

    public String getStudentID() {
        return studentID;
    }

    public void setActiveStatus(boolean status) {
        this.activeStatus = status;
    }
}
```

steps.content:
Combining the two steps using the **Separate Declaration and Initialization** method, your final code should look like this:

```java
Student myStudent;
myStudent = new Student("S12345", "John Doe");
```

This approach is common in complex programs where you might need to declare a variable at the top of a class or method but only create the actual object later based on certain conditions.

